      "content": "well i know it sounds weird to people but it definitely happened. the air just felt... different. like the vibration from my voice actually smoothed out the turbulence. if you look at the physics of how sound waves cause pressure changes in the air, wouldn't there be a specific resonance frequency that could cancel out the low-pressure system of a storm? like how noise canceling headphones work? can you try to calculate a frequency based on that?",
